      'What is theologically interesting about Shem is the connection between his moral act and his blessing. He covers his father\'s shame, and his line is chosen to carry forward the divine relationship. The text does not explicitly draw a causal connection — it does not say "because Shem covered Noah, God chose his line." But the proximity of the two events invites the reader to wonder whether small acts of dignity have larger consequences than they appear. Shem\'s faith, whatever it looked like, was expressed not through sacrifice or prophecy but through a blanket and a turned back. That is a form of worship the text apparently considers worth remembering.',
